<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Benazir Bhutto leads boycott of parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISLAMABAD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PAKISTAN'S former prime minister Benazir Bhutto led an opposition boycott of
the parliament's lower house yesterday after clashing with the government
over an alleged attempt to kill her last month, Reuter reports from
Islamabad.
Ms Bhutto and other deputies of her People's Democratic Alliance (PDA)
marched out of the house after Gohar Ayub Khan, the National Assembly
speaker, gave short shrift to their accusations.
Shujaat Hussain, the Interior minister, denied the PDA charge that ruling
party members attacked Ms Bhutto's caravan with gunfire, stones and sticks
when she visited Multan in Punjab province last month to meet victims of
devastating floods.
Ms Bhutto blamed members of the Pakistan Moslem League (PML) party of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif for the September 23 attack, which she branded a
conspiracy.
'This is a black day in the history of this parliament,' Ms Bhutto said
later. The alliance would decide its next move today, she added.
On Saturday, a court acquitted Ms Bhutto's husband Asif Ali Zardari of
masterminding the murder of 29 people.
Prison officials said Mr Zardari, who was arrested in October 1990, was
still being held to face other charges, although this acquittal was his
fifth so far.
</TEXT>
