FT  12 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Firstland makes Pounds 5m move into
packaging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WALTON MORAIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIRSTLAND Group proposes to buy Gelpack Industrial, a private industrial
packaging company, for Pounds 4.8m under a reorganisation that will
transform the USM-quoted oil and gas company into a packaging business
listed on the main market, writes Walton Morais.
Firstland, suspended since September 15 pending the reorganisation, will
change its name to Britton Group and fund the acquisition by a placement of
102m new ordinary shares with private and institutional investors to raise
Pounds 5.1m before expenses.
Mr Simon Beart, finance director, who with Mr Robin Williams, chief
executive, led a management buy-in last March with the aim of diversifying
into an industrial group with stable earnings, said Gelpack was involved in
a low-volume, high-margin niche sector of a growing market.
It had been showing strong growth in pre-tax profit recently, jumping from
Pounds 214,000 in the year ended June 30 1990 to Pounds 706,000 in 1991 and
Pounds 1.05m in 1992. Turnover expanded from Pounds 7.93m to Pounds 11.03m
and Pounds 11.55m.
Firstland will want to dispose of its remaining oil and gas business
quickly; probably below the estimated book value of Pounds 3m for its
operating oil and gas wells in Oklahoma and the Gulf of Mexico.
The reorganisation will include a capital reduction and elimination of the
deficit on the profit and loss account.
Barring unforeseen circumstances, the directors intend to recommend a final
dividend payable in mid-1993 for the year 1992.
For the first half Firstland reduced its loss from Pounds 455,000, which
included a Pounds 285,000 exceptional charge, to Pounds 87,000, on turnover
of Pounds 201,000 (Pounds 233,000). Losses per share were 0.34p (2.05p).
</TEXT>
