<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Gloom worsens in financial services sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PICTURE of deepening gloom and pessimism in Britain's financial services
companies emerges from the quarterly survey of business confidence in the
sector published by the Confederation of British Industry and Coopers &amp;
Lybrand today.
The report says that financial services companies are delaying new
investments because they are worried about their business prospects and
believe they risk making a net loss on any developments they plan.
In contrast to the second quarter of the year, when companies were
increasingly confident about their business prospects, many of the 300
companies surveyed - ranging from banks and building societies to
stockbrokers and venture capitalists - saw their business volumes dwindle
between July and September.
The fall in volumes affected both wholesale and personal business and was
followed by a sharp drop in confidence, particularly among building
societies, securities traders and fund managers.
The only improvement came from business with overseas customers.
There was some good news, however, for the financial services sector. Income
from fees and commissions rose strongly and lenders widened their average
spreads, but banks said their margins and fee income had improved more
slowly than expected.
Almost all financial services companies are cutting costs sharply for the
fourth quarter in succession. Banks, finance houses, and securities traders
lead the way, although insurance brokers say that their total costs have
strongly increased.
While the squeeze on costs has led to a continuing fall in the numbers
employed in the sector, the drop was not as sharp in the third quarter of
the year as it was in the second.
Staff costs make up a much smaller proportion of total company costs than
they did a year ago.
Financial services companies expect the cost-cutting to continue for the
rest of the year, but the resulting profitability gains are partly offset by
their non-performing loans.
In order to help themselves through the recession, financial services
companies are holding back on spending capital on developing their
businesses.
The survey reports significant cuts in planned spending on land and
buildings, as well as on vehicles, plant, and machinery over the next 12
months. There are also signs that companies will spend less on developing
computer systems and on information technology generally next spring.
The only chink of light in the generally gloomy scene seems to be that most
companies expect profits to rise slightly in the last three months of the
year, as fewer bad debts and lower costs take their effect.
Financial Services Survey, September 1992. CBI, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford
Street, London WC1A 1DU. Subscription Pounds 120 CBI members, Pounds 195
non-members.
</TEXT>
