<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Optimism in commerce falls sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LATEST survey of business confidence in the UK, published yesterday by
Dun and Bradstreet International, the business information company, shows
the sharpest decline in expectations for profits, sales and new orders in
commerce since the spring of 1990.
The report, the first national survey of business confidence since the
government was forced to suspend sterling from the European exchange rate
mechanism on September 16, reflects deepening gloom in most sectors of the
economy.
In two areas, retailing and construction, the outlook seems particularly
bleak. According to the survey, retailers anticipate declining sales volumes
in spite of an aggressive price-cutting strategy, while most building firms
are forecasting static order books at best.
The overall survey of business confidence - in which 1,900 managing
directors throughout the UK were interviewed - discloses a marked decline in
optimism over sales volumes.
Six out of 10 companies expect no upturn in sales in the final quarter of
this year, while 39 per cent actually expect sales to decrease. Dun and
Bradstreet's optimism index, a method of calculating business confidence,
shows that the current quarter-to-quarter decline is the steepest since the
fourth quarter of 1989 and the first of 1990.
The bleak outlook for sales is matched by a severe decline in expectation of
profits. Only 21 per cent of companies predicted improved profits in the
next three months. For the first time for more than a year, Dun and
Bradstreet has found that more businesses are expecting profits to decrease
rather than to increase in the ensuing three months.
Analysing its survey by sectors, Dun and Bradstreet found that retailers
remained among the most pessimistic - with 46 per cent saying they expected
sales to fall in the final quarter of this year. According to the report,
suppliers to the retail sector will suffer greatly and will find orders very
thin on the ground.
There was deepening gloom in the construction sector, where 61 per cent of
companies expect further declines in sales in the next quarter and 67 per
cent predict reduced profits.
The most bullish sector appeared to be manufacturing - being the only one
apart from services where managers were willing to raise stock levels in
anticipation of increased sales.
One of the few bright spots in the survey was the outlook for exports. There
was a smaller fall in the optimism over exports than in the optimism over
retail sales. According to Dun and Bradstreet: 'The most confident exporter
sectors are services and durable manufacturers who will be hoping to reap
the benefits of the floating pound.'
Nevertheless, the fall in export optimism was the largest for two years.
Confidence in an export-led recovery does not appear as strong as might have
been expected after sterling's devaluation.
Chemists and drugstores are proving far more resilient to the recession than
most other retailers, according to a report from Verdict, the retail
consultants.
The study found that the sector was underpinned by shoppers who were
continuing to buy essential health and personal-care products.
Sales in the sector rose 8 per cent to Pounds 8.3bn last year, outstripping
the 5.5 per cent increase in total retail sales. However, slowing inflation
has limited sales increases in the chemists and drugstores sector to about 5
per cent in the current year.
Verdict says that, in spite of diversification, traditional pharmacists are
still highly dependent on prescriptions, which account for 46 per cent of
their sales.
Chemists and Drugstores. Verdict Research, 112 High Holborn, London. Pounds
695.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
