<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Call to speed up road planning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIME it takes to get big road construction schemes under way could be
cut from 13 years to four under radical proposals published by the National
Economic Development Office today, Richard Tomkins writes.
Nedo's report comes just days after Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary,
announced an urgent investigation into the reasons for the long delays in
planning road schemes.
At present, most big trunk road and motorway schemes take up to 13 years to
bring to construction because of long-winded public consultation procedures.
Nedo believes a streamlined procedure would prove popular with road-scheme
opponents and cut planning time. It proposes that:
The Department of Transport should publish a 10-year plan for all forms of
transport.
The DoT should hand over responsibility for roadbuilding to an executive
agency that could compete with the private sector for contracts.
The first stage of any road scheme would be a conference of interested
parties to agree a tentative plan.
That would be subjected to an environmental impact assessment, then put on
display for public comment before being submitted for planning permission.
An inquiry could still be held, but would consider only matters of detail.
Once the plan was published, anyone affected would be able to sell their
land at market value plus a bonus of 20 per cent. If they opposed the scheme
at a public inquiry, they would lose the bonus.
A New Approach to Road Planning. Nedo Books, Millbank Tower, Millbank,
London SE1P 4QX. Pounds 35 plus Pounds 1.20 p&amp;p.
</TEXT>
