FT  12 OCT 92 / World News in Brief: European Monetary System
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Speculation that the Bundesbank will cut official interest rates helped to
ease tensions in the exchange rate mechanism grid last week. The French
franc, arguably the best barometer of the stability of the grid's core
currencies, ended at FFr3.388 against the D-Mark, although it continues to
be protected by France's high interest rates. Pressure on the weakest three
currencies, the punt, escudo and peseta, remained strong, with all three
currencies close to their ERM floors against the D-Mark. Currencies, Page
27; UK fund managers, Page 17; UK gilts, Page 20; The chart shows the member
currencies of the exchange rate mechanism measured against the weakest
currency in the EMS's narrow 2.25 per cent fluctuation band. In practice,
currencies in the narrow band cannot rise more than 2.25 per cent from the
weakest currency in that part of the system. The Spanish peseta and
Portuguese escudo operate with 6 per cent fluctuation bands.
