<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / French threaten summit boycott in trade row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE has threatened to boy-cott this week's emergency European Community
summit in Birmingham if the EC makes concessions to the US on subsidised
farm trade in negotiations which opened in Brussels yesterday.
The French threat risks derailing the finely balanced talks which are widely
seen as the last chance this year to settle a two-year farm trade dispute
which has stalled plans - the so-called Gatt Uruguay Round - to liberalise
world trade.
Last night, Mr Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, said no progress
had been made at Brussels. 'We are much too far from the goal,' he said,
adding that France wanted an accord 'but not to the detriment of its vital
interests'.
EC officials were told last week that French president Francois Mitterrand
would refuse to attend the Birmingham summit if he was put under pressure to
endorse concessions in the Uruguay Round that were unacceptable to his
government.
The message was delivered by Mr Jean-Pierre Soisson, the French farm
minister, during talks in Brussels with Mr Jacques Delors, European
Commission president, and Mr Frans Andriessen, the Dutch commissioner
responsible for external affairs. Mr Soisson also warned of a farmers'
revolt if new concessions were made, according to several EC officials.
Mr Ray MacSharry, EC agriculture commissioner, offered France assurances
before yesterday's meeting that any agreement would require consensus within
the Community, although Paris technically cannot veto a deal. 'It is not a
matter of out-voting the French,' he said. Until today's resumption of the
talks - which could continue tomorrow - both sides are saying nothing on the
detail of the negotiations.
An official said: 'Everyone is very conscious of the situation in France at
the moment. The French farm minister has been making it plain in Brussels
how difficult it is going to be to achieve support in France for the kind of
Uruguay Round deal that negotiators are currently talking about.'
A French boycott of Birmingham would sink hopes of presenting a much-needed
display of EC unity.
French fears have risen in response to signals that President George Bush is
anxious to seal a deal in order to bolster his re-election campaign.
Likewise, US farm lobbies last week warned that the administration was on
the brink of a 'sell-out'.
Yesterday's Brussels talks, held amid very tight secrecy. involved Mrs Carla
Hills, special US trade representative, Mr Andriessen, Mr MacSharry, and Mr
Ed Madigan, the US agriculture secretary.
First to meet were Mrs Hills and Mr Andriessen. Apart from farm trade, it
was expected that they would discuss obstacles to settlement of the Uruguay
Round - principally disputes over multilateral tariff cuts and
liberalisation of world trade in services.
France is Europe's leading ex-porter both of services and farm products. It
had been hoped that French negotiators could be persuaded to accept
concessions on subsidised food exports - its farm trade accounts for just
3.2 per cent of its GDP - in return for significant gains in services.
But French officials say they have little flexibility in the light of the
powerful No vote by French farmers on Maastricht.
Progress on farm talks has been blocked on two critical issues:
The EC's refusal to accept a 24 per cent cut in the volume of subsidised
farm exports in addition to a 36 per cent cut in their value.
EC insistence that compensation to European farmers for price cuts agreed in
May's reform of the Common Agricultural Policy should not be regarded as
subsidies. The proposed Uruguay Round agreement demands a 20 per cent cut in
domestic farm subsidies over six years.
EC negotiators will be pressing for a smaller volume cut - a figure of 21
per cent has been mentioned - and for 'aggregation', which would allow the
EC to make smaller cuts in sensitive areas, counterbalanced by deeper cuts
elsewhere.
EC officials plan stiff defence of policy powers, Page 2
Pandora's box or a panacea, Page 14
Editorial Comment, Page 14
