<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Treasury put gloss on projections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT told Treasury economists to put a more favourable gloss on
official projections for the UK's growing public sector deficit, published a
month before the April general election.
In an internal note, the chancellor told officials to recalculate their
projections for the public sector borrowing requirement in the five years to
1996-97, to reduce them, if possible, to zero by the end of the period.
This led the Treasury to publish projections for the cumulative deficits in
the three years to 1996-97 that were roughly Pounds 30bn below the original
figures worked out internally.
Mr Lamont's initiative was designed to ensure that the Budget statement
published in March, which also contained the latest Treasury forecasts,
would not include figures about government deficits that would unsettle
financial markets and the public.
Details of the manoeuvrings will intensify pressure on Mr Lamont to clarify
the degree to which Treasury economists provide analysis free from political
pressures.
Mr Lamont's future is in some doubt after the pound's suspension from the
exchange rate mechanism and his lacklustre reception at last week's Tory
conference.
Seven months after Mr Lamont moved to cut the Treasury's PSBR projections,
he is attempting to trim back next year's public spending because of renewed
fears over rising state borrowing triggered by the recession.
The chancellor put pressure on his officials in a note drafted about a week
before the Budget statement on March 10.
The note was sent on Mr Lamont's behalf by Mr Jeremy Heywood, his principal
private secretary.
After Mr Lamont's request, the Treasury settled for a compromise, in which
the PSBR projection for 1996-97 was set in the Budget statement at Pounds
6bn, above Mr Lamont's zero target but less than the initial estimate of
Pounds 16bn.
Treasury projections, Page 8
</TEXT>
