<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Rabin threatens to crush unrest: Jerusalem fears stepped-up
intifada may derail peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Israeli government, worried that a surge of unrest in the occupied
territories might derail Middle East peace talks, yesterday warned
Palestinians that Israeli troops would use all their strength to suppress
unrest in the occupied territories.
'The Palestinians must understand that the solution to their problems will
be around the negotiating table, not in the streets and alleyways of the
territories,' Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin said during a visit to the Gaza
Strip. Troops would use 'all our strength' to suppress Palestinian unrest.
At least two Palestinians, one a boy aged 14 and an Israeli settler, were
killed over the weekend, and more than 100 injured in the West Bank and
Gaza. The clashes with security forces are similar to the widespread rioting
which characterised the early days of the near-five-year-old intifada, or
uprising, against Israeli rule.
The demonstrations erupted in support of a hunger strike staged by many of
the 12,000 Palestinian prisoners held in Israeli jails, protesting at
conditions in the prisons.
Mr Rabin said he was ready to improve conditions. But Israeli officials
accused opponents and supporters of the peace talks on the Palestinian side
of exploiting the protest. They said opponents wanted to disrupt the
year-old negotiations, which are due to resume in Washington on October 21,
while supporters were trying to put pressure on Israel.
The authorities are afraid of a sustained resurgence of the intifada. 'We
are worried,' said a Rabin aide. 'This can undermine the whole peace
process.'
The unrest reflected frustration in the occupied territories that the talks
have so far produced nothing tangible.
One Palestinian lawyer said: 'Feelings are running very strong on the prison
issue because almost everyone has a family member in jail. The street has
taken over again; our peace negotiators cannot control it.'
</TEXT>
