<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Bush and Clinton stand their ground in TV debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush and Governor Bill Clinton fought each other to a
reasonably civilised stand-off in their first televised debate of the US
presidential election last night.
Neither the Republican nor the Democratic contender committed an obvious,
egregious mistake in the first of their three confrontations over the next
eight days. Both were well prepared and, if Mr Bush appeared initially the
more relaxed, Mr Clinton warmed to his task. Mr Ross Perot, the independent
candidate, generated the most applause and laughter with his epigrammatic
interventions at the debate in St Louis, Missouri.
The closest the debate came to fireworks was early on when the president
insisted that Mr Clinton was wrong to have participated in demonstrations
against the Vietnam war while a student at Oxford. 'I couldn't do that and I
don't think most Americans could,' Mr Bush said.
Mr Clinton responded by comparing the president's attacks on his patriotism
to the tactics of the late Senator Joseph McCarthy in the 1950s. He cited Mr
Bush's father, Prescott Bush, at the time a senator from Connecticut, as a
man who had spoken out against McCarthyism.
Mr Bush's frequently repeated theme was one of optimism. He said more than
once that 'America is not coming apart at the seams', as he said Mr Clinton
consistently implied, and that the US was 'still the envy of the world'.
He emphasised in his closing statement that experience and trust were the
special qualities he brought to the election. Mr Clinton's equally
consistent message was that the time had come for change at home and abroad.
Mr Perot, in perhaps the only intervention of his that might be seen as
helpful to Mr Clinton, said the president was wrong to focus on what his
Democratic opponent had done as a youth.
In one possible surprise, Mr Bush hinted that, if re-elected, he would 'tell
Jim Baker to do in domestic affairs what you've done in foreign affairs'. It
had been generally assumed Mr Baker would return to the State Department in
any Bush second term.
Mr Clinton ducked an invitation to attack the Federal Reserve for its
conduct of monetary policy. If he became president, he said, 'I don't have
to worry in the short term about the Fed, their policies seem to me pretty
sound'. It was more important, he argued, 'to use the powers the president
does have' over the economy.
The Democratic candidate probably scored most heavily in his detailed
responses on issues such as health care, the need for racial harmony and a
proper understanding of the problems of contemporary families.
The first instant reaction came from an ABC TV poll, which found that 27 per
cent thought Mr Clinton had won, 22 per cent Mr Perot and 18 per cent Mr
Bush, with the rest undecided. Asked for their presidential preferences,
compared to the previous poll, Mr Clinton went up one point to 46 per cent,
Mr Bush down 4 points to 31 per cent and Mr Perot up 7 points to 15 per
cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
