<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / MacGregor backs ERM camp: Transport secretary stresses he
would favour early re-entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John MacGregor, recently cited as a possible future chancellor, yesterday
lined up squarely with senior cabinet colleagues backing Britain's early
return to the European exchange rate mechanism.
The transport secretary's unequivocal support for re-entry to the ERM as
soon as feasible will disappoint those who saw him as less controversially
'European' than Mr Kenneth Clarke, the home secretary and the other widely
tipped contender for chancellor.
In repeated statements since Britain left the ERM on September 16, Mr John
Major, the prime minister, has felt obliged to stress that there is no
question of Mr Norman Lamont being removed from the chancellorship.
However, speculation over Mr Lamont's medium-term future has continued,
fuelled by the poor reception from commentators and the City to his speech
at the Conservative party conference in Brighton last week.
The question mark over the chancellor provoked widespread discussion at the
fringes of the conference - itself fiercely divided over the desirability of
UK membership of the ERM - as to his likely successor.
While a straight switch of jobs between Mr Lamont and Mr Clarke was cited as
one option for the prime minister, some argued that Mr MacGregor, a former
chief secretary to the Treasury, would be a less controversial alternative.
But Euro-sceptics rallying to Mr Lamont made clear such a move would still
be viewed as a serious shift in the delicate balance of influences on the
prime minister towards the most vehemently pro-Maastricht Europeans.
In a BBC television interview, Mr MacGregor made plain yesterday that he was
closely allied to Mr Clarke, Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, and Mr
Michael Heseltine, the trade secretary, in the strongly pro-ERM faction of
the cabinet.
Their opponents are Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, Mr Peter
Lilley at social security and Mr Michael Portillo, the chief secretary. Mr
Lamont's official backing for a return 'when circumstances allow' is widely
viewed as indicating scant enthusiasm for any such move.
Taking care to pledge unqualified support for the chancellor's decision to
leave the mechanism, the transport secretary said unprecedented currency
flows had left no alternative, although the exit was 'a great pity'. He
added: 'Once we have sorted out what needs to be done to produce an ERM, or
post-ERM, that will assist the Community with dealing with those currency
flows, then we should be back in it.'
As a new round of discussions on public expenditure begins this week, the
transport secretary made clear that a balance had to be found between
defending capital expenditure programmes and current spending on welfare
benefits. He hinted strongly that restraints on public sector pay rises were
almost certain to be part of the equation now being examined by Mr Lamont's
so-called EDX committee on the expenditure round.
