<DATE>921012
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 OCT 92 / Left group backs student loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSTITUTE for Public Policy Research, a leftwing think tank, has
proposed moving further towards student loans and means-tested fees to
finance expansion in higher education.
The Labour party has hitherto opposed student loans and charges for higher
education, but the think tank says the present system of student finance
'supports the wealthiest young people in society at the expense of the
majority'. However, it says that the government's current loan scheme
achieves the worst of all worlds: it deters students and fails to raise
revenue.
It says that the primary constraint on expanding higher education is the
cost to government, and proposes that any reform of student funding should
raise revenue while distributing costs more fairly.
The report says students should be funded through loans paid back through
the tax system when they earn above the national average.
Other proposals include modularised courses to increase choice and
flexibility; a two-semester academic year; and separate funding for teaching
and research.
Higher Education: Expansion and Reform. IPPR, 30 Southampton Street, London
WC2E 7RA. Pounds 9.95.
</TEXT>
