<HEADLINE>
FT  10 OCT 92 / Savimbi may drop threats of war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES were rising last night that Angola's mercurial rebel leader, Mr Jonas
Savimbi, would back away from threats of resuming guerrilla war and agree to
take part in a government of national unity following the country's first
free elections.
US assistant secretary of state Herman Cohen said Mr Savimbi was likely to
emerge from isolation in his southern stronghold of Huambo to come to Luanda
to accept President Jose Eduardo dos Santos' invitation of talks on a
government of reconciliation.
'We feel that there is still time and still grounds for optimism,' said Mr
Cohen.
Earlier, Miss Margaret Anstee, the United Nations special envoy, visited Mr
Savimbi, in the first meeting he has had with an international observer
since last week's elections put President Dos Santos and his MPLA government
well in the lead.
Unita has alleged electoral fraud and threatened to return to guerrilla war.
Miss Anstee said last night Mr Savimbi had said he would accept the poll
result if an investigation demanded by Unita proved there had been no fraud.
The critical question is whether Mr Savimbi is trying to exploit the fears
of a return to civil war to force concessions from the government on a
post-electoral set-up or whether he is unable to compromise and determined
to go back to war.
'The problem is that none of us knows what Savimbi's bottom line is,' said a
western diplomat.
'After all these years of external support he remains an enigma and nobody,
not even Washington and Pretoria, has any leverage on him.'
In the past week, Mr Savimbi has challenged the election results, withdrawn
his generals from the newly unified army and retreated from Luanda to Huambo
 -the politically symbolic southern city from which he launched his
guerrilla struggle in 1975.
If Mr Savimbi is merely playing a dangerous game of high-stakes
brinkmanship, as seems more likely, it remains unclear what concessions he
will accept. Given that he won 40 per cent of the national vote, observers
say neither party can rule alone.
Possible compromises, dubbed by a Portuguese minister as 'disappointment
management', are being considered in Luanda, including a second round of
presidential elections, a genuine power-sharing arrangement at national and
provincial levels and the idea of a joint administration.
A second round looks most likely to keep Mr Savimbi in the peace process but
it is doubtful if he would win.
However, nobody knows whether Mr Savimbi, after 30 years of bush warfare and
internal propaganda, is psychologically able to accept anything less than
the presidency.
The second problem is convincing the government, and particularly the MPLA
hardliners, to bend over backwards to make concessions after a democratic
victory.
Western observers say hopes for preventing a return to civil war rest on the
fact that in the post-cold war era and after free elections Mr Savimbi can
no longer expect the military and diplomatic support he received from
Washington and Pretoria between 1975 and 1991.
Referring to the possibility of renewed warfare, Mr Cohen said Unita knew
'this is an impossible procedure. There will be absolutely no support in the
international community or internally for such an operation.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
